# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apple-of-discord
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] In Greek mythology, **Abderus** or **Abderos** (Ancient Greek: Ἄβδηρος, romanized: *Ábdēros*) was a divine hero, reputed by some to be one of Heracles' lovers (eromenoi), and reputedly a son of Hermes by some accounts, and eponym of Abdera, Thrace.
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] Apollodorus say he was the son of the god Hermes and a native of Opus in Locris, whilst according to Strabo, he was the son of Thromius the Locrian.
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] Pindar makes Abderus a son of Poseidon and Thronia, while Photius writes that he was brother of Patroclus, and according to Hellanicus (who considers him the son of Hermes), he was Heracles' lover.
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] Abderus was mostly known for his tragic role in Heracles' Eighth Labor.
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] Along with others, he helped Heracles capture the four savage mares of Diomedes the king of the Thracian Bistones.
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] Heracles overpowered the grooms and drove the Mares of Diomedes into the sea and left them in the care of Abderus.
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] However, while Heracles was away the horses killed Abderus, either by dragging him behind them after he lost control of them, or by devouring him.
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] Heracles was heartbroken upon Abderus's death, weeping, hugging and wailing over what remained of his lover.
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] Heracles buried Abderus in a cermonial tomb, with a bowl containing a kalos inscription of affection.
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] Heracles then founded the city of Abdera near Abderus's tomb, where *agones* (Greek: ἀγῶνες), athletic games consisting of boxing, pancratium and wrestling were held in his honor (but chariot races were banned in respect of how he died).
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] Abderus' presence in surviving artistic sources is uncertain.
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] In scenes where Heracles is present along with the horses and a figure on the ground or being consumed, there nothing that distinguishes the body as that of Abderus as opposed to that of the groom or Diomedes himself.
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] His presence is likewise unclear on several intaglios from the 1st-2nd centuries BCE which probably show the labour.
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] A man, presumed to be Diomedes, is lying in a manger, about to be devoured by the horses looming over him while a naked youth stands to the side.
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] There is nothing that would positively identify the figure as Abderus, but he is the only youth associated with the story.
[src:apple-of-discord/abderus] Thus, if the scene is indeed that of Diomedes being eaten by the horses, Abderus is a likely candidate for the identity of the figure (the other possibility being the groom).
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] Academus, the site, was sacred to Athena, the goddess of wisdom, and other immortals; it had since the Bronze Age sheltered her religious cult, which was perhaps associated with the hero-gods, the Dioskouroi (Castor and Polydeukes), and for the hero Akademos.
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] By classical times the name of the place had evolved into the *Akademeia*.
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] It had also earlier been called *Ecademia* (Ἑκαδημία).
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] According to Plutarch, Cimon converted this, "waterless and arid spot into a well watered grove, which he provided with clear running-tracks and shady walks".
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] Its sacred grove furnished the olive oil that was distributed as prizes in the Panathenaic Games and contained in the finely decorated Panathenaic amphorae presented to the winners.
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] Plutarch, in his biography of the Athenian king Theseus (the slayer of the Minotaur), writes that, after being widowed and reaching age 50, the king abducted the 12-year-old child Helen (long before she married Menelaus, met Paris and was the cause of the Trojan War).
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] Due to this outrage, her twin brothers Castor and Pollux invaded Attica to liberate their sister and threatened to destroy Athens.
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] Academus saved the city by telling them where she was hidden, at Aphidnae.
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] Also for this reason Tyndareus (a Spartan king and the father of Castor and stepfather of Helen) showed Academus much gratitude.
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] Academe was the site of Plato's Academy and within its groves, he gave his lectures.
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] According to Diogenes Laertius, Dion, "bought for Plato the little garden which is in the Academy".
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] Diogenes Laertius, notes Timon of Phlius observes that there Plato "a big fish, but a sweet-voiced speaker, musical in prose as the cicada who, perched on the trees of Hecademus, pours forth a strain as delicate as a lily".
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] The phrase "the groves of Academe" comes from Horace's *Epistles,* 20 b.c.): *Atque inter silvas academi quaerere verum* (To seek for truth in the groves of Academe)'.
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] John Milton, in Paradise Regained book 4, 244-245, uses the phrase: "See there the Olive Grove of Academe, Plato's retirement, where the Attic Bird Trills her thick-warbl'd notes the summer long".
[src:apple-of-discord/academus] Mary McCarthy made the phrase the title of her satirical novel *The Groves of Academe*.
[src:apple-of-discord/aceso] Aceso was the daughter of Asclepius and Epione, sister of Iaso, Hygieia, Panacea, and Aegle.
[src:apple-of-discord/aceso] Unlike her sister Panacea (Cure-All), she represented the process of curing rather than the cure itself.
[src:apple-of-discord/aceso] Her male counterpart was Acesis (Akesis).
[src:apple-of-discord/aceso] In Greek sculptural reliefs, Aceso appears alongside her father Asclepius and sisters Hygeia, Panacea, Aegle, and Iaso.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] The **Achaeans** or **Akhaians** (/əˈkiːənz/; Ancient Greek: Ἀχαιοί, romanized: *Akhaioí*, "the Achaeans" or "of Achaea") is one of the names in Homer which is used to refer to the Greeks collectively.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] The term "Achaean" is believed to be related to the Hittite term **Ahhiyawa** and the Egyptian term **Ekwesh** which appear in texts from the Late Bronze Age and are believed to refer to the Mycenaean civilization or some part of it.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] In the historical period, the term fell into disuse as a general term for Greek people, and was generally reserved for inhabitants of the region of Achaea, a region in the north-central part of the Peloponnese.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] The city-states of this region later formed a confederation known as the Achaean League, which was influential during the 3rd and 2nd centuries BC.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] According to Margalit Finkelberg, the name Ἀχαιοί (earlier Ἀχαιϝοί) is possibly derived, via an intermediate form *Ἀχαϝyοί, from a hypothetical older Greek form reflected in the Hittite form *Aḫḫiyawā*; the latter is attested in the Hittite archives, e.g. in the Tawagalawa letter.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Beekes doubted its validity and suggested a Pre-Greek **Akaywa-*.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] In Homer, the term Achaeans is one of the primary terms used to refer to the Greeks as a whole.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] It is used 598 times in the *Iliad*, often accompanied by the epithet "long-haired".
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Other common names used in Homer are **Danaans** (/ˈdæneɪ.ənz/; Δαναοί *Danaoi*; used 138 times in the *Iliad*) and **Argives** (/ˈɑːrɡaɪvz/; Ἀργεῖοι *Argeioi*; used 182 times in the *Iliad*).
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] **Panhellenes** (Πανέλληνες *Panhellenes,* "All of the Greeks") and **Hellenes** (/ˈhɛliːnz/; Ἕλληνες *Hellenes*) both appear only once.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] All of the aforementioned terms were used synonymously to denote a common Greek identity.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] In some English translations of the *Iliad*, the Achaeans are simply called the **Greeks** throughout.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Later, by the Archaic and Classical periods, the term "Achaeans" referred to inhabitants of the much smaller region of Achaea.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Herodotus identified the Achaeans of the northern Peloponnese as descendants of the earlier, Homeric Achaeans.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] According to Pausanias, writing in the 2nd century AD, the term "Achaean" was originally given to those Greeks inhabiting the Argolis and Laconia.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Pausanias and Herodotus both recount the legend that the Achaeans were forced from their homelands by the Dorians, during the legendary Dorian invasion of the Peloponnese.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] They then moved into the region later called Achaea.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] A scholarly consensus has not yet been reached on the origin of the historic Achaeans relative to the Homeric Achaeans and is still hotly debated.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Former emphasis on presumed race, such as John A.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Scott's article about the blond locks of the Achaeans as compared to the dark locks of "Mediterranean" Poseidon, on the basis of hints in Homer, has been rejected by some.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] The contrasting belief that "Achaeans", as understood through Homer, is "a name without a country", an *ethnos* created in the Epic tradition, has modern supporters among those who conclude that "Achaeans" were redefined in the 5th century BC, as contemporary speakers of Aeolic Greek.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Karl Beloch suggested there was no Dorian invasion, but rather that the Peloponnesian Dorians were the Achaeans.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Eduard Meyer, disagreeing with Beloch, instead put forth the suggestion that the real-life Achaeans were mainland pre-Dorian Greeks.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] His conclusion is based on his research on the similarity between the languages of the Achaeans and pre-historic Arcadians.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] William Prentice disagreed with both, noting archeological evidence suggests the Achaeans instead migrated from "southern Asia Minor to Greece, probably settling first in lower Thessaly" probably prior to 2000 BC.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Some Hittite texts mention a nation to the west called **Ahhiyawa** (Hittite: 𒄴𒄭𒅀𒉿 *Aḫḫiyawa*).
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] In the earliest reference to this land, a letter outlining the treaty violations of the Hittite vassal Madduwatta, it is called *Ahhiya*.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Another important example is the *Tawagalawa Letter* written by an unnamed Hittite king, most probably Hattusili III, of the empire period, the 14th–13th century BC, to the king of *Ahhiyawa*, treating him as an equal and implying Miletus (*Millawanda*) was under his control.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] It also refers to an earlier "*Wilusa* episode" involving hostility on the part of *Ahhiyawa*.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Ahhiya(wa) has been identified with the Achaeans of the Trojan War and the city of Wilusa with the legendary city of Troy.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Note the similarity with early Greek Ϝιλιον *Wilion*, later Ἴλιον *Ilion*, the name of the acropolis of Troy.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Emil Forrer, a Swiss Hittitologist who worked on the Boghazköy tablets in Berlin, said the Achaeans of pre-Homeric Greece were directly associated with the term "Land of Ahhiyawa" mentioned in the Hittite texts.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] His conclusions at the time were challenged by other Hittitologists (i.e.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Johannes Friedrich in 1927 and Albrecht Götze in 1930), as well as by Ferdinand Sommer, who published his *Die Ahhijava-Urkunden* (*The Ahhiyawa Documents*) in 1932.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] The exact relationship of the term *Ahhiyawa* to the Achaeans beyond a similarity in pronunciation was hotly debated by scholars, even following the discovery that Mycenaean Linear B is an early form of Greek; the earlier debate was summed up in 1984 by Hans G.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] More recent research based on new readings and interpretations of the Hittite texts, as well as of the material evidence for Mycenaean contacts with the Anatolian mainland, has led to the widely supported conclusion that Ahhiyawa refers to the Mycenaean world, or at least to a part of it.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Scholars have proposed several possible locations for the Ahhiyawa capital: Rhodes in the Dodecanese Mycenae in the Argolid and Thebes in Boeotia.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] It is possible that the political center of Ahhiyawa was not fixed in a single location, but may have shifted over time—perhaps initially based in Thebes and later in Mycenae.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] It has been proposed that *Ekwesh* of the Egyptian records may relate to *Achaea* (compared to Hittite *Ahhiyawa*), whereas *Denyen* and *Tanaju* may relate to Classical Greek *Danaoi*.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] The earliest textual reference to the Mycenaean world is in the Annals of Thutmosis III (c.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] 1479–1425 BC), which refers to messengers from the king of the Tanaju, c.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] 1437 BC, offering greeting gifts to the Egyptian king, in order to initiate diplomatic relations, when the latter campaigned in Syria.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Tanaju is also listed in an inscription at the Mortuary Temple of Amenhotep III.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] A list of the cities and regions of the Tanaju is mentioned in this inscription.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Among the cities listed are Mycenae, Nauplion, Kythera, Messenia and the Thebaid (region of Thebes).
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] During the 5th year of Pharaoh Merneptah, a confederation of Libyan and northern peoples is supposed to have attacked the western delta.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Included amongst the ethnic names of the repulsed invaders is the Ekwesh or Eqwesh, whom some have seen as Achaeans, although Egyptian texts specifically mention these Ekwesh to be circumcised.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Homer mentions an Achaean attack upon the delta.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Menelaus speaks of the same in Book IV of the *Odyssey* to Telemachus when he recounts his own return home from the Trojan War.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Some ancient Greek authors say that Helen had spent the time of the Trojan War in Egypt, and not at Troy, and that after Troy the Greeks went there to recover her.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] In Greek mythology, the perceived cultural divisions among the Hellenes were represented as legendary lines of descent that identified kinship groups, with each line being derived from an eponymous ancestor.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] Hellen, Graikos, Magnes, and Macedon were sons of Deucalion and Pyrrha, the only people who survived the Great Flood.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] The *ethne* were said to have originally been named *Graikoi* after the elder son but later renamed *Hellenes* after Hellen who was proved to be the strongest.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] The sons of Hellen and the nymph Orseis were Dorus, Xuthos, and Aeolus.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] The sons of Xuthos and Kreousa, daughter of Erechthea, were Ion and Achaeus.
[src:apple-of-discord/achaeans-homer] According to Hyginus, 22 Achaeans killed 362 Trojans during their ten years at Troy.
[src:apple-of-discord/acharaca] The city was founded by Antiochus I Soter in the first half of the 3rd century BC.
[src:apple-of-discord/acharaca] The city had an oracle of Pluto and Kore (Persephone) at Acharaca.
[src:apple-of-discord/acharaca] A large grove, a Doric temple (remains of which survive), and a cave called the Charonium, were the seat of the oracle.
[src:apple-of-discord/acharaca] Strabo noted that "The sick resort thither, and live in the village near the cave, among experienced priests, who sleep at night in the open air and direct the mode of cure by their dreams.
[src:apple-of-discord/acharaca] The priests invoke the gods to cure the sick, and frequently take them into the cave, where they remain in quiet without food for several days.
[src:apple-of-discord/acharaca] Sometimes the sick themselves observe their own dreams, but apply to the priests to interpret them.
[src:apple-of-discord/acharaca] Strabo also describes a festival held at Acharaca.
[src:apple-of-discord/acharaca] An annual festival, to which there is general resort, is celebrated at Acharaca, and at the time particularly are to be seen and heard those who frequent it, conversing about cures performed there.
[src:apple-of-discord/acharaca] During this feast the young men of the gymnasium and the ephebi, naked and anointed with oil, carry off a bull by stealth at midnight, and hurry it away into the cave.
[src:apple-of-discord/acharaca] It is then let loose, and after proceeding a short distance falls down and expires.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] The **Acheron** (/ˈækərən/ or /ˈækərɒn/; Ancient Greek: Ἀχέρων *Acheron* or Ἀχερούσιος *Acherousios*; Greek: Αχέροντας *Acherontas*) is a river in the Epirus region of northwest Greece.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] In Greek mythology, Acheron is often depicted as the entrance to the Greek Underworld where souls must be ferried across by Charon (although some later sources, such as Roman poets, assign this role to the river Styx).
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] It is 52 km (32 mi) long, and has a drainage area of 705 km2 (272 sq mi).
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] The river's source is located near the village Zotiko, in the southwestern part of the Ioannina regional unit.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] The Acheron flows into the Ionian Sea in Ammoudia, near Parga.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] Ancient Greek mythology saw the Acheron, sometimes known as the "river of woe", as one of the five rivers of the Greek underworld.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] Most classical accounts, including Pausanias (10.28) and later Dante's *Inferno* (3.78), portray the Acheron as the entrance to the Underworld and depict Charon ferrying the souls of the dead across it.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] Ancient Greek literary sources such as Pindar, Aeschylus, Euripides, Plato, and Callimachus also place Charon on the Acheron.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] Roman poets, including Propertius, Ovid, and Statius, name the river as the Styx, perhaps following the geography of Virgil's underworld in the *Aeneid,* where Charon is associated with both rivers.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] The Homeric poems describe the Acheron as a river of Hades, into which Cocytus and Phlegethon both flowed.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] The Roman poet Virgil called the Acheron the principal river of Tartarus, from which the Styx and the Cocytus both sprang.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] The newly dead would be ferried across the Acheron by Charon in order to enter the Underworld.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] The Suda describes the river as "a place of healing, not a place of punishment, cleansing and purging the sins of humans".
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] According to later traditions, Acheron had been a son of Helios and either Gaia or Demeter, who was turned into the Underworld river bearing his name after he refreshed the Titans with drink during their contest with Zeus.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] By this myth, Acheron is also the father of Ascalaphus by either Orphne or Gorgyra.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] The river called Acheron with the nearby ruins of the Necromanteion (oratory of the dead) is found near Parga on the mainland of Greece opposite Corfu.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] Another branch of Acheron was believed to surface at the Acherusian cape (now Karadeniz Ereğli in Turkey) and was seen by the Argonauts according to Apollonius of Rhodes.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] Greeks who settled in Italy identified the Acherusian lake into which Acheron flowed with Lake Avernus.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] Plato in his *Phaedo* identified Acheron as the second greatest river in the world, excelled only by Oceanus.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] He claimed that Acheron flowed in the opposite direction from Oceanus beneath the earth under desert places.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] The word is also occasionally used as a synecdoche for Hades itself.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] Virgil mentions Acheron with the other infernal rivers in his description of the underworld in Book VI of the *Aeneid*.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] The Acheron was sometimes referred to as a lake or swamp in Greek literature, as in Aristophanes' *The Frogs* and Euripides' *Alcestis*.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] In Dante's *Inferno*, the Acheron river forms the border of Hell.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] Following Greek mythology, Charon ferries souls across this river to Hell.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] Those who were neutral in life sit on the banks.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] Acheron Lake in Antarctica is named after the mythical river.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] Several English naval vessels have been named HMS *Acheron*.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] There is a stream named the *Dry Acheron* in Canterbury, New Zealand.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] The Eocene turtle genus *Acherontemys* of the Roslyn Formation in North America was named in reference to the Acheron mythos.
[src:apple-of-discord/acheron] Acheron Fossae form large troughs north of Olympus Mons on the Mars northern hemisphere.
[src:apple-of-discord/acherusia] The lake to which this belief seems to have been first attached was the Acherusia in Thesprotia, through which the river Acheron flowed.
[src:apple-of-discord/acherusia] Other lakes or swamps of the same name, and believed to be in connection with the lower world, were near Hermione in Argolis, near Heraclea in Bithynia, between Cumae and cape Misenum in Campania, and lastly in Egypt, near Memphis.
[src:apple-of-discord/acherusia] In Greek mythology, it was also the name of a cavern through which Heracles dragged Cerberus as one of his Twelve Labors.
[src:apple-of-discord/acherusia] In Plato's *Phaedo*, souls are divided into four different categories.
[src:apple-of-discord/acherusia] Evil souls are sent to Tartarus; good souls are sent onward to pure places of the world; but neutral souls as well as repentant people who performed great crimes are not immediately sent to their next realm.
[src:apple-of-discord/acherusia] Neutral souls are cleansed in the Acherusian Lake before proceeding onward, similar to good souls but slower.
[src:apple-of-discord/acherusia] People who committed great evil yet were repentant can hope their victims invite them into Acherusia where they can undergo the cleansing process.
[src:apple-of-discord/acherusia] Early Christianity adopted various terms and concepts from Greek mythology, especially among Greek pagans who converted to Pauline Christianity, including the Acherusian Lake, Elysian Fields, and Hades.
[src:apple-of-discord/acherusia] The early Greek Christian view seems especially influenced by the fate of the fourth group described by Plato, with Acherusia a place for repentant sinners to be cleansed, possibly at the invitation of those whom they wronged.
[src:apple-of-discord/acherusia] The 2nd-century Apocalypse of Peter describes how prayers for the dead by saints in heaven would move God to give a postmortem baptism or washing of damned souls in hell in the Acherusian Lake, allowing them into paradise after a period of cleansing suffering.
[src:apple-of-discord/acherusia] The account in the Apocalypse of Peter is quoted in the *Sibylline Oracles* and several other works.
[src:apple-of-discord/acherusia] In the 4th-century Apocalypse of Paul, the archangel Michael washes souls in the Acherusian Lake before their entry into the City of Christ in Paradise.
[src:apple-of-discord/acherusia] The 3rd- to 5th-century Apocalypse of Moses features a story where Adam is washed in the Acherusian Lake before being brought to converse with God, presumably to ensure his ritual purity.
[src:apple-of-discord/apple-of-discord] In Greek mythology, the **Apple of Discord** (Ancient Greek: μῆλον τῆς Ἔριδος) was a golden apple thrown by Eris, the goddess of strife, at the wedding of Peleus and Thetis.
[src:apple-of-discord/apple-of-discord] She was not invited to the wedding and threw it out of anger to ruin the gathering (after showing up uninvited).
[src:apple-of-discord/apple-of-discord] It sparked a vanity-fueled dispute among Hera, Athena, and Aphrodite that led to the Judgement of Paris and ultimately the Trojan War.
[src:apple-of-discord/apple-of-discord] In common parlance, the "apple of discord" is the core, kernel, or crux of an argument, or a small matter that could lead to a bigger dispute.
[src:apple-of-discord/apple-of-discord] In the Eixample district of Barcelona, there is a block nicknamed in Spanish **La manzana de la discordia** (Catalan: *Illa de la Discòrdia*).
[src:apple-of-discord/apple-of-discord] The reason for this usage is that the word **manzana** means both "apple" and "city block" in Spanish.
[src:apple-of-discord/apple-of-discord] It was so named ("block of discord") because it features four different interpretations of *Modernisme* architecture: Antoni Gaudí's Casa Batlló, Lluís Domènech i Montaner's Casa Lleó Morera, Josep Puig i Cadafalch's Casa Amatller, and Enric Sagnier's Casa Mulleras.
[src:apple-of-discord/apple-of-discord] In some later sources, Eris inscribed on the apple "for the fairest" or "to the most beautiful" before tossing it.
[src:apple-of-discord/apple-of-discord] The most popular version of the inscription in Greek is τῇ καλλίστῃ (transliterated: *tē(i) kallistē(i)*, "for/to the most beautiful").
[src:apple-of-discord/apple-of-discord] *Καλλίστῃ* is the dative singular of the feminine superlative of *καλός*, "beautiful".
[src:apple-of-discord/apple-of-discord] In Latin sources, the word is **formosissima**.
[src:apple-of-discord/apple-of-discord] In an attempt to rationalize the myth, Ptolemaeus Chennus wrote that instead of an apple, the three goddesses fought over which would get a man named Melus ("apple") as her priest, with Paris deciding in favour of Aphrodite.
